  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent money laundering. These typically include:\n\n1. Customer Due Diligence (CDD)\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Conducting background checks\n- Monitoring suspicious transactions\n- Reporting unusual financial activities\n\n2. Regulatory Compliance\n- Adhering to Anti-Money Laundering (AML) laws\n- Implementing comprehensive compliance programs\n- Maintaining transaction records\n- Filing suspicious activity reports\n\n3. Risk Assessment\n- Identifying potential money laundering risks\n- Developing risk management strategies\n- Conducting regular internal audits\n\n4. Reporting Requirements\n- Reporting large cash transactions\n- Submitting suspicious transaction reports\n- Cooperating with law enforcement investigations\n\n5. Training\n- Providing employee training on money laundering detection\n- Ensuring staff understand legal obligations\n- Maintaining updated knowledge of regulatory changes\n\n6. International Standards\n- Following guidelines from organizations like FATF\n- Implementing cross-border transaction monitoring\n- Sharing information with international regulatory bodies\n\nThese obligations are designed to prevent financial crimes and protect the integrity of the global financial system.",
